What to submit

This assignment is to be completed individually and submitted to CloudDeakin. By the due date, you are required to submit the following files to the corresponding Assignment (Dropbox) in CloudDeakin:

  1. [YourID]_assignment2_solution.ipynb: This is your Python notebook solution source file.
  2. [YourID]_assingment2_output.html or [YourID]_assingment2_output.pdf: This is the output of your Python notebook solution exported in HTML or PDF format.
  3. Extra files needed to complete your assignment, if any (e.g., images used in your answers).

For example, if your student ID is: 123456, you will then need to submit the following files:

  • 123456_assignment2_solution.ipynb
  • 123456_assignment2_output.html

Warning

Some components of this assignment may involve heavy computation that runs for a long duration. Please start early to avoid missing the assignment due date.

Marking criteria

Your submission will be assessed based on the overall impact of your effort. A useful model (or application) should be your focus. But as in Assignment 1, we will also consider the following criteria at the same time.

  • Showing good effort through completed tasks.
  • Applying deep learning theory to design suitable deep learning solutions for the tasks.
  • Critically evaluating and reflecting on the pros and cons of various design decisions.
  • Demonstrating creativity and resourcefulness in providing unique individual solutions.
  • Showing attention to detail through a good quality assignment report.

Assignment objective¶

This assignment is to feedback on your learning in deep learning theory and its application to data analytics or artificial intelligence problems.

It builds on Assignment 1 but requires a higher level of mastery of deep learning theory and programming/engineering skills. In particular, you will practice making design decisions yourself. You are also likely to encounter practical issues that will help you consolidate textbook learning.

Task 1 (P Task) Smart Recycling using Deep Learning¶

In Assignment 1, you tackled the image classification problem in Fashion-MNIST. There, you used a Densely Connected Neural Network. In Assignment 2, you will apply the best practices of deep-learning computer vision to make something useful for our planetwaste classification.

Background Every day, we put things into our recycle bin, to reduce landfill waste. However, we may unintentionally contribute to recycling contamination by "wish recycling" the wrong items. As every city council has slightly different rules for recycling, you will build a technological solution to ensure you only recycle things that are permitted by your local council. More discussions about recycling contamination can be found here.

Task 1.1 Define a problem¶

Define an image classification problem that may help people better recycle, particularly by reducing contamination.

Describe the desired inputs and outputs, including the target classes.

Task 1.2 Make a plan¶

What dataset can you use to develop a deep learning solution?

How many images do you need? How many for training? How many for testing?

Do you need to label the images yourself?

How do you determine if your model is good enough?

Task 1.3 Implement a solution¶

Collect relevant data. Develop a deep learning model. Report the model performance against the success criteria that you define.

# Task 1.1 Define a problem:

# This task seems like it is a multiclass classification problem.
# Ie. we have a smart bin which takes any garbage as an input, and then classifies it to a respective waste class.
# Using this waste class, it decides if it is recyclable or not.
# With strong accuracy, this would reduce recycling contamination when sent to landfill.


# This task will require a convolution neural network of a to be specified architecture.
# This will require high resolution images of rubish as inputs.
# This means we will need to train on a dataset of images of all different kinds of waste.
# The outputs of this neural net will be 8 nodes representing each class, the output of a softmax function.
# With one hot encoding, the output will be matched to the corresponding classification vector.

# To obtain the target classes, I have referenced the Geelong council (my local council) and their recycling guide.

# Source: https://www.geelongaustralia.com.au/bins/article/item/8cb963227c7b661.aspx
# Source: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2RkTdSj93GI

# The target classes of this neural network will be the following:

# 0 - Cardboard (Recyclable)
# 1 - Clear Paper (Recyclable)
# 2 - Empty Glass (Recyclable)
# 3 - Metal Food Packaging (Recyclable)
# 4 - Rigid Plastic (Recyclable)
# 5 - Soft Plastic (Non-Recyclable)
# 6 - Plastic Toys (Non-Recyclable)
# 7 - Clothing (Non-Recyclable)
# 8 - Foot Wear (Non-Recyclable)

# Note: I have omitted the used nappies and the polystyrene classes, as I was unable to find suitable data for these classes.

# Like image augmentation and using a pretrained model as a feature extractor.

# Task 1.3 Implement a solution:

# Obtaining the data:
# Using the Trashnet image dataset from their Github then adding some of my own images and images from an another datset.
# Source: https://github.com/garythung/trashnet
# Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/alejopaullier/guie-toys-dataset

batch_size = 16
img_dim = 256
img_size = (img_dim, img_dim)

waste_dir = "/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/Dataset - Assignment 2/Geelong Waste Dataset" # The dataset I have constructed from my listed sources.

x_train = keras.preprocessing.image_dataset_from_directory(directory = waste_dir, 
                                                 labels = "inferred", 
                                                 color_mode = "rgb", 
                                                 batch_size = batch_size, 
                                                 image_size = img_size, 
                                                 shuffle = True, 
                                                 seed = 123, 
                                                 validation_split = 0.2, 
                                                 subset = "training")

x_val = keras.preprocessing.image_dataset_from_directory(directory = waste_dir, 
                                                 labels = "inferred", 
                                                 color_mode = "rgb", 
                                                 batch_size = batch_size, 
                                                 image_size = img_size, 
                                                 shuffle = True, 
                                                 seed = 123, 
                                                 validation_split = 0.2, 
                                                 subset = "validation")

  fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows = 1, ncols = 4, figsize = (15, 10))
  fig.tight_layout(pad = 2) # Image spacing.
  for n in range(0, 4):

# Preprocessing, one hot encoding and normalization.

def pre_process(images, labels):
  norm_images = tf.image.convert_image_dtype(image = images, dtype = tf.float32)
  one_hot_labels = tf.one_hot(labels, depth = 9)
  return (images, one_hot_labels)

x_train_one_hot = x_train.map(pre_process).cache().repeat() # Repeat method to generate an infinite dataset.
x_val_one_hot = x_val.map(pre_process).cache().repeat()
In [ ]:
# Building the Model.

# Model 1, basic convolutional neural net, with no regularization.

waste_mod_1 = models.Sequential(layers = [layers.Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3, 3), input_shape = (img_dim, img_dim, 3), activation = "relu"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = "relu"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Flatten(), 
                                          layers.Dense(units = 512, activation = "relu"),  
                                          layers.Dense(units = 9, activation = "softmax")])

waste_mod_1.compile(optimizer = "rmsprop", loss = "categorical_crossentropy", metrics = ["accuracy"])

# Model 2, with dropout layer added after the first dense layer, also added an extra conv2d layer and adjusted the filter sizes.

waste_mod_2 = models.Sequential(layers = [layers.Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3, 3), strides = (1, 1), input_shape = (img_dim, img_dim, 3), activation = "relu"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = "relu"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Flatten(), 
                                          layers.Dropout(rate = 0.4), 
                                          layers.Dense(units = 512, activation = "relu"), 
                                          layers.Dense(units = 9, activation = "softmax")])

waste_mod_2.compile(optimizer = "rmsprop", loss = "categorical_crossentropy", metrics = ["accuracy"])
In [ ]:
# Less epochs for fitting this model, 30 seemed too high for the previous one.

waste_mod_2.fit(x = x_train_one_hot, epochs = 20, steps_per_epoch = 100, validation_data = x_val_one_hot, validation_steps = 100)

waste_mod_2.save("/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/Assignment Two Models/waste_mod_2")

# Model 3, extra convolutional layer added, each convolutional layer initialized with he_normal, dropout layer increased to 0.6 and a slower learning rate for RMSprop.

waste_mod_3 = models.Sequential(layers = [layers.Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3, 3), strides = (1, 1), input_shape = (img_dim, img_dim, 3), activation = "relu", kernel_initializer = "he_normal"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu", kernel_initializer = "he_normal"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu", kernel_initializer = "he_normal"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = "relu", kernel_initializer = "he_normal"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu", kernel_initializer = "he_normal"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 512, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu", kernel_initializer = "he_normal"), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Flatten(), 
                                          layers.Dropout(rate = 0.6), 
                                          layers.Dense(units = 512, activation = "relu"), 
                                          layers.Dense(units = 9, activation = "softmax")])

waste_mod_3.compile(optimizer = keras.optimizers.RMSprop(learning_rate = 0.0001), loss = "categorical_crossentropy", metrics = ["accuracy"])

                                          layers.BatchNormalization(), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu", kernel_initializer = "he_normal"), 
                                          layers.BatchNormalization(), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu", kernel_initializer = "he_normal"), # Conv Block 2.
                                          layers.BatchNormalization(), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu", kernel_initializer = "he_normal"), 
                                          layers.BatchNormalization(), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu", kernel_initializer = "he_normal"), # Conv Block 3.
                                          layers.BatchNormalization(), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu", kernel_initializer = "he_normal"), 
                                          layers.BatchNormalization(), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = "relu", kernel_initializer = "he_normal"), # Conv Block 4.
                                          layers.BatchNormalization(), 
                                          layers.Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = "relu", kernel_initializer = "he_normal"), 
                                          layers.BatchNormalization(), 
                                          layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)), 
                                          layers.Flatten(), 
                                          layers.Dropout(rate = 0.7), 
                                          layers.Dense(units = 512, activation = "relu"), 
                                          layers.Dense(units = 9, activation = "softmax")])

Build a data preprocessing pipeline to perform data augmentation. (You may use Keras ImageDataGenerator or write your own transformations.)

  • Report the model performance with the pipeline added. How much performance gain have you achieved?

  • Profile your input pipeline to identify the most time-consuming operation. What actions have you taken to address that slow operation? (Hint: You may use a profiler such as the TensorFlow Profiler.)

Task 2.2 Compare the performance under equal training time¶

You may notice that with your pipeline, the model performance improves, but at the cost of a longer training time per epoch. Is the additional training time well spent? Compare the dynamic of model performance (e.g., classification accuracy on the test data) with and without data augmentation, when equal training time is spent in the two scenarios.

Task 2.3 Identifying model strength and weakness¶

Identify images that are incorrectly classified by your model. Do they share something in common? How do you plan to improve the model's performance on those images?

# Task 2.1 Build an input pipeline for data augmentation:

# Building my own pipeline with tf.image.

def waste_data_augmentation(images, labels):
  """Takes a Tensorflow dataset as its input, and performs various data transformations to the images within it."""

  img_size = 256

  image = tf.image.convert_image_dtype(image = images, dtype = tf.float32)
  image = tf.image.random_flip_left_right(image = image)
  image = tf.image.random_flip_up_down(image = image)
  image = tf.image.rot90(image = image)
  image = tf.image.random_saturation(image = image, lower = 0, upper = 2)
  image = tf.image.random_brightness(image = image, max_delta = 0.5)
  image = tf.image.random_crop(image, size = (img_size, img_size, 3))

  return (image, labels)

# Task 2.3 Identifying model strength and weakness:

# Looking at the batches in the validation set:

def correctly_predicted(val_data, batch_size):
  """Takes a batch of images from a tensorflow dataset object, returns a collection of subplots titled with the predicted and actual class of the image."""

  # 0 - Cardboard (Recyclable)
  # 1 - Clear Paper (Recyclable)
  # 2 - Empty Glass (Recyclable)
  # 3 - Metal Food Packaging (Recyclable)
  # 4 - Rigid Plastic (Recyclable)
  # 5 - Soft Plastic (Non-Recyclable)
  # 6 - Plastic Toys (Non-Recyclable)
  # 7 - Clothing (Non-Recyclable)
  # 8 - Foot Wear (Non-Recyclable)

  pred_batch = val_data.unbatch().batch(batch_size).take(1) # This allows for a larger batch size so we can get a bigger sample.

  batch_1_pred = waste_mod_augment.predict(x = pred_batch)
  predicted_class = np.argmax(a = batch_1_pred, axis = 1) # np.argmax will return the index of the 1 value from the one-hot encoding, corresponding to the class.

  for images, labels in pred_batch:
    actual_class = np.argmax(a = labels.numpy(), axis = 1)

  for images, labels in pred_batch:
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows = 3, ncols = 10, figsize = (30, 10))
    fig.tight_layout(pad = 2)
    for n in range(0, batch_size):
      ax.flat[n].imshow(X = images.numpy().astype("uint32")[n])
      ax.flat[n].set(title = f"Predicted: {predicted_class[n]}, Actual: {actual_class[n]}")

  return plt.show()

# Function for accuracy on the new test set.
# This could have been done by importing a sklearn function, but thought I'd just do it myself.

def test_accuracy(data_batch):
  """Takes a batch of data, feeds it into a model and then returns the accuracy of the model on that batch."""

  predictions = aug_waste_mod_rd.predict(x = data_batch)

  pred_class = np.argmax(a = predictions, axis = 1)

  for images, labels in data_batch:
    actual_classes = np.argmax(a = labels.numpy(), axis = 1)

  num_correct = 0
  
  for i in range(0, pred_class.shape[0]):
    if pred_class[i] == actual_classes[i]:
      num_correct = num_correct + 1
  
  acc_score = num_correct/pred_class.shape[0]

  return acc_score

# Training the last block of the VGG16 architecture.

convolutional_base.trainable = True

set_trainable = False
for layer in convolutional_base.layers:
    if layer.name == 'block5_conv1' or "block5_conv2" or "block5_conv3":
        set_trainable = True
    if set_trainable:
        layer.trainable = True
    else:
        layer.trainable = False

Assignment Summary:

From all of the experimentation throughout the assignment, I am reasonably happy with how the model has turned out. Almost attaining the 70% accuracy on the validation set during the data augmentation stages was a very nice outcome.

If I had more time to experiment, I would play around with more model architectures and try out some much deeper neural nets with residual connections. I believe this would help with a lot with generalizability and be very useful for this kind of task.

Also, I would have liked to have collected more data, this would have improved things signifigantly. It was very difficult to get data that matched the Geelong council recycling guide. This hindered things a little bit and if I had more time (such as in a real world project) I would have spent a long period of time obtaining a large dataset. I believe if I had a larger dataset I could have achieved an 80 + % accuracy and that would have been an excellent outcome.
